message.content: Billy Snedden was an Australian politician who served as the leader of the Liberal Party from 1972 to 1975. He was born on December 31, 1926, in Perth, Western Australia. Snedden was a member of the Australian House of Representatives for 25 years, representing the division of Bruce. He held several ministerial positions, including Attorney-General, Minister for Labour and National Service, and Treasurer. Snedden also served as the Speaker of the House of Representatives from 1976 until his death in 1987. He was known for his advocacy of liberal economic policies and his commitment to the principles of social justice.

Bobby Fischer was an American chess prodigy, grandmaster, and the eleventh World Chess Champion. Born on March 9, 1943, in Chicago, Illinois, Fischer is widely considered one of the greatest chess players of all time. He gained significant fame in the world of chess at a young age, becoming a grandmaster and the U.S. Chess Champion at just 15. In 1972, he captured global attention when he ended 24 years of Soviet domination of the World Championship by defeating Boris Spassky in Reykjavik, Iceland. Fischer's eccentric personality, marked by controversial and reclusive behavior, also drew significant public attention. He passed away in Iceland in 2008.

Joseph Jaquet was a renowned Swiss sculptor, known for his exceptional work in the field of art during the 19th century. Born in 1822 in Geneva, Switzerland, Jaquet's artistic talent was evident from a young age. He studied at the School of Fine Arts in Geneva and later in Paris, where he was greatly influenced by the neoclassical style. His sculptures, often depicting historical or mythological figures, were celebrated for their intricate detail and emotional depth. Jaquet's work was widely exhibited, earning him numerous awards and recognition. He passed away in 1898, leaving behind a significant legacy in the world of sculpture.

Mihai Eminescu was a renowned Romanian poet, novelist, and journalist, often regarded as the most famous and influential Romanian poet. Born on January 15, 1850, in Botoșani, Romania, Eminescu's work encompassed every genre of poetry (from love poems to philosophical verses), as well as prose and journalism. His most notable works include "Luceafărul," "Odă în metru antic," and "Scrisorile." Eminescu's work significantly influenced the Romanian culture and his poems have been translated into over 60 languages. He passed away on June 15, 1889, but his legacy continues to inspire and influence the world of literature.

Douglas Wood is a renowned engineer known for his significant contributions to the field of engineering. He has held several high-ranking positions in various engineering firms, demonstrating his expertise and leadership skills. Wood has been instrumental in the development and implementation of innovative engineering solutions, earning him recognition and respect in the industry. His work has spanned across multiple sectors, including construction, manufacturing, and technology. Throughout his career, Wood has consistently demonstrated a commitment to excellence, innovation, and sustainable practices in engineering.

Steve Cummins is an accomplished professional in the field of technology and business. He is the co-founder and CEO of WorkGrid Software, a company that focuses on simplifying the workday for employees by integrating various systems into one digital platform. Prior to this, he served as the Director of IT Business Operations at Liberty Mutual Insurance. Cummins has a proven track record of leading teams to deliver innovative technology solutions that drive business value. He holds a Bachelor's degree in Computer Science from the University of New Hampshire.

Lina Marulanda was a renowned Colombian television presenter and model. Born on May 15, 1980, in Medellín, Colombia, she began her modeling career at the age of 12 and later transitioned into television. She was best known for her work as a presenter on Caracol Television's breakfast news show, "Day to Day". Marulanda was also a successful businesswoman, owning a modeling agency and a line of cosmetics. Tragically, she died by suicide on April 22, 2010, at the age of 29.

Fidel Castro was a Cuban revolutionary and politician who served as the Prime Minister of Cuba from 1959 to 1976 and then as the President of the Council of State and the President of the Council of Ministers from 1976 to 2008. Born on August 13, 1926, in Birán, Cuba, Castro led the 26th of July Movement in a successful revolution against the authoritarian government of Cuban President Fulgencio Batista in 1959. His socialist policies and alignment with the Soviet Union during the Cold War led to strained relations with the United States, culminating in the Bay of Pigs invasion and the Cuban Missile Crisis. Castro's administration was marked by human rights abuses, economic sanctions, and emigration reforms. He passed away on November 25, 2016.

Rory Burns is a professional English cricketer who was born on August 26, 1990, in Epsom, Surrey, England. He is a left-handed opening batsman who plays for Surrey County Cricket Club and the England national team. Burns made his debut for Surrey in 2012 and has since become a key player for the team, earning the captaincy in 2018. He made his international debut for England in November 2018 against Sri Lanka. Known for his patience and technique, Burns has established himself as a reliable opener in Test cricket.

Danny Faure is a Seychellois politician who served as the President of Seychelles from 16 October 2016 to 26 October 2020. Born on 8 May 1962, Faure was educated in Cuba and Tanzania before returning to Seychelles in 1985. He began his political career as a member of the People's Party and held various ministerial positions, including Minister of Education, before becoming Vice President in 2010. He assumed the presidency following the resignation of his predecessor, James Michel. During his tenure, Faure focused on issues such as climate change, economic reform, and social cohesion.

Tappaya Sit-Or is a renowned Thai artist, best known for his contemporary paintings that often incorporate traditional Thai motifs and styles. Born in 1947 in Bangkok, Thailand, he studied at the College of Fine Art and later at the Faculty of Painting, Sculpture, and Graphic Arts at Silpakorn University. His work has been exhibited in numerous solo and group exhibitions both in Thailand and internationally. Sit-Or's unique style, which blends traditional Thai art with modern techniques and themes, has earned him a significant place in the Thai art scene.

Esteban Espíndola is an Argentine professional footballer who plays as a defender. Born on 24th April 1993 in San Miguel de Tucumán, Argentina, Espíndola began his career with local club San Martín. He later moved to Honduras, where he played for several clubs including Real España. In 2019, he signed with Australian A-League club Central Coast Mariners. Espíndola has also represented the Honduras national team at the international level, despite being born in Argentina.

Nonzee Nimibutr is a renowned Thai film director and producer, best known for his work in the horror and fantasy genres. Born on January 20, 1962, in Nonthaburi, Thailand, he studied at the College of Fine Art and later at the Visual Arts Department of the Faculty of Fine and Applied Arts at Chulalongkorn University. His breakthrough came in 1997 with the film "Dang Bireley's and Young Gangsters". Nonzee is often credited with revitalizing the Thai film industry and paving the way for a new wave of Thai cinema. His other notable works include "Nang Nak", a box office hit, and "Jan Dara", a controversial film that pushed the boundaries of Thai censorship laws.

Carl Braun was a prominent Austrian obstetrician and gynecologist, born on February 22, 1822, in Vienna, Austria. He is best known for his significant contributions to the field of obstetrics, particularly his work on the mechanics of labor and delivery. Braun was a professor at the University of Vienna, where he taught obstetrics and gynecology. He also served as the director of the university's maternity clinic. His research and teachings greatly influenced the practice of obstetrics, leading to safer childbirth procedures. Braun passed away on September 25, 1891.

Jorge Enríquez is a professional Mexican footballer who was born on January 8, 1991, in Zapopan, Jalisco, Mexico. He is best known for his role as a defensive midfielder. Enríquez began his career with C.D. Guadalajara, a club he joined in 2008 and played for until 2017. He has also played for other clubs such as Club León, Club Santos Laguna, and Club Tijuana. In addition to his club career, Enríquez has represented Mexico at various levels internationally, including the U-23 team that won the gold medal at the 2012 Summer Olympics in London.

Thomas Piketty is a renowned French economist, best known for his work on wealth and income inequality. He was born on May 7, 1971, in Clichy, Hauts-de-Seine, France. Piketty studied at the École Normale Supérieure and the London School of Economics, and he earned his PhD from the School for Advanced Studies in the Social Sciences (EHESS) and the London School of Economics. He is a professor at EHESS and at the Paris School of Economics. Piketty gained international fame for his book "Capital in the Twenty-First Century" (2013), which argues that the rate of capital return in developed countries is persistently greater than the rate of economic growth, and that this will cause wealth inequality to increase in the future.

Idi Amin Dada was a military dictator in Uganda from 1971 to 1979. He was born around 1925 in Koboko, in West Nile Province of what is now Uganda. Amin joined the King's African Rifles (KAR) of the British Colonial Army in 1946 as a cook. He rose through the ranks, becoming a lieutenant in 1961, a year before Uganda gained its independence from Britain. Amin seized power in a military coup in 1971, ousting President Obote. His rule was characterized by gross human rights abuses, political repression, and corruption. He was known for his unpredictable behavior and his love for pomp and ceremony. Amin was forced into exile in 1979, first in Libya, then Iraq, and finally in Saudi Arabia, where he died in 2003.

Paul Anka is a Canadian-American singer, songwriter, and actor who gained fame in the late 1950s with hit songs like "Diana", "Lonely Boy", and "Put Your Head on My Shoulder". Born on July 30, 1941, in Ottawa, Canada, Anka started his music career as a teenager and quickly rose to stardom. He is also known for writing well-known music such as the theme for The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson and one of Tom Jones's biggest hits, "She's a Lady". Anka's contributions to the music industry have earned him a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame and an induction into the Songwriters Hall of Fame.

Marli Renfro is an American former model and actress, best known for her role as Janet Leigh's body double in the famous shower scene of Alfred Hitchcock's film, "Psycho" in 1960. Born on August 19, 1938, in Los Angeles, California, she was also one of the first Playboy Playmates, appearing in the September 1960 issue of the magazine. Renfro's career in the entertainment industry was brief, spanning only a few years in the early 1960s. Despite her short stint in Hollywood, her contribution to one of the most iconic scenes in film history has cemented her place in cinematic lore.

Noel Malicdem is a professional darts player from the Philippines who competes in events of the Professional Darts Corporation (PDC). Born on December 27, 1977, Malicdem began his professional career in 2009. He has represented his country in several international competitions, including the World Cup of Darts. Malicdem gained international recognition when he reached the second round of the 2019 PDC World Darts Championship. Known for his consistent performances, he is considered one of the top darts players in the Philippines.

Karl Urban is a New Zealand actor best known for his roles in Hollywood blockbusters such as "The Lord of the Rings" trilogy, "Star Trek," and "Thor: Ragnarok." Born on June 7, 1972, in Wellington, New Zealand, Urban developed an interest in acting at a young age and began his career in local theater productions. He made his film debut in the 1992 movie "Once in Chunuck Bay." Urban's breakthrough role came when he was cast as Eomer in "The Lord of the Rings" trilogy. Since then, he has continued to star in a variety of films and television series, including "The Chronicles of Riddick," "Dredd," and "The Boys."

Jeffrey Viggiano is a professional actor and voice-over artist based in New York City. He has been involved in the entertainment industry for over a decade, with a diverse range of roles in film, television, and theater. Viggiano is known for his work in "The Blacklist" (2013), "The Deuce" (2017), and "The Marvelous Mrs. Maisel" (2017). He is also a skilled voice-over artist, lending his voice to numerous commercials, video games, and animated series. Viggiano is a member of the Screen Actors Guild‐American Federation of Television and Radio Artists (SAG-AFTRA) and Actors' Equity Association (AEA).

Matt Hunter is an American-Colombian singer and songwriter, best known for his bilingual singing abilities in both English and Spanish. Born on February 14, 1998, in New York City, Hunter began his career as a voice actor for the popular children's network, Nickelodeon, before transitioning into music. He gained significant recognition in Latin America with his debut single "Mi Amor" in 2011, which quickly became a hit. Since then, he has released several successful singles and albums, solidifying his place in the Latin pop music scene.

Kubota Beisen was a renowned Japanese painter, art critic, and educator during the Meiji period. Born on January 26, 1852, in Edo, Japan, Beisen was known for his traditional Japanese paintings, particularly in the Nihonga style. He was a disciple of the famous painter, Shiokawa Bunrin, and later studied Western-style painting under Charles Wirgman. Beisen was instrumental in the development of Western-style art education in Japan, serving as a professor at the Tokyo School of Fine Arts. He also wrote several books on art theory and criticism. Beisen passed away on November 8, 1906.

Clancy Brown is an American actor and voice artist, best known for his roles in films such as "The Shawshank Redemption" and "Starship Troopers", as well as his voice work in animated series like "SpongeBob SquarePants". Born on January 5, 1959, in Urbana, Ohio, Brown began his acting career in the early 1980s. He has since built a diverse portfolio, playing characters in various genres, from dramas and thrillers to comedies and animated features. Brown's distinctive deep voice has also made him a sought-after voice actor, lending his voice to characters in video games, animated films, and television series.

Roman Anatolyevich Pavlyuchenko is a retired Russian professional footballer who was born on December 15, 1981, in Mostovskoy, Russia. He played as a striker and is best known for his time with the English Premier League club, Tottenham Hotspur, and the Russian national team. Pavlyuchenko began his career with Dynamo Stavropol and then moved to Rotor Volgograd before joining Spartak Moscow, where he gained prominence. He represented Russia in the 2008 and 2012 UEFA European Championships and the 2010 FIFA World Cup. After retiring from professional football, Pavlyuchenko transitioned into politics, serving as a deputy in the Krasnodar Regional Legislative Assembly.

Irina Shayk, born Irina Valeryevna Shaykhlislamova on January 6, 1986, is a renowned Russian model and actress. She gained international recognition in 2007 when she became the exclusive face of Intimissimi lingerie and landed the cover of Sports Illustrated Swimsuit Issue in 2011. Shayk made her acting debut in the 2014 film "Hercules." She has also appeared in high-profile advertising campaigns for brands like Guess, Victoria's Secret, and Lacoste. Shayk was in a relationship with Portuguese footballer Cristiano Ronaldo from 2010 to 2015, and with American actor Bradley Cooper from 2015 to 2019, with whom she has a daughter.

Suthida Vajiralongkorn, also known as Suthida Tidjai, is the Queen Consort of Thailand since 2019. She was born on June 3, 1978, in Hat Yai, Songkhla, Thailand. Before her marriage to King Maha Vajiralongkorn, she was a flight attendant for Thai Airways. She later joined the Royal Thai Army and rose to the rank of general. She has been awarded numerous royal decorations for her service. Her marriage to the king was announced unexpectedly on May 1, 2019, just days before his coronation.

Julie Bishop is an Australian politician who served as the Minister for Foreign Affairs from 2013 to 2018 and the deputy leader of the Liberal Party from 2007 to 2018. Born on July 17, 1956, in Lobethal, South Australia, she studied law at the University of Adelaide and practiced as a commercial litigation lawyer before entering politics. Bishop was first elected to the House of Representatives in 1998, representing the seat of Curtin in Western Australia. Throughout her political career, she held several ministerial positions, including Minister for Education, Science and Training, and Minister for Ageing. She is known for being the first woman to hold the position of Australia's Minister for Foreign Affairs.

Ahsee Tuala is a professional rugby union player from Samoa. He was born on March 4, 1989, in Apia, Samoa. Tuala is known for his versatility on the field, playing both fullback and wing positions. He began his professional career with the Samoan team, and later moved to the Northampton Saints in the English Premiership in 2014. Tuala has also represented Samoa at the international level, making his debut in 2014. He has since become a key player for the national team, representing Samoa in the Rugby World Cup.

Diego Suarez was a renowned garden designer, best known for his work on the Villa I Tatti in Florence, Italy. Born in 1888 in Venezuela, Suarez moved to Italy in his early twenties where he developed a passion for garden design. He was a close friend of art historian Bernard Berenson, who commissioned him to design the gardens of Villa I Tatti. The garden, which is considered one of the finest examples of the Italian Renaissance style, is a testament to Suarez's skill and creativity. His design incorporated a series of terraces, fountains, and an exquisite pebble mosaic, all set against the backdrop of the Tuscan countryside. Suarez passed away in 1974, leaving behind a legacy of beautiful garden designs.

Ayman al-Zawahiri is an Egyptian physician and Islamic theologian who became a prominent leader within Al-Qaeda, a militant Sunni Islamist multi-national organization. Born on June 19, 1951, in Cairo, Egypt, he was raised in a well-educated family deeply involved in political and religious debates. He was introduced to political Islam at a young age and joined the Muslim Brotherhood when he was just 14. He later became one of the founding members of the Egyptian Islamic Jihad, a group dedicated to the overthrow of the Egyptian government. After the assassination of Al-Qaeda's leader, Osama bin Laden, in 2011, al-Zawahiri was announced as the new leader of the organization. He is currently one of the world's most wanted terrorists.

Gopi Sundar is an acclaimed Indian music director, singer, and songwriter, primarily known for his work in the Malayalam and Telugu film industries. Born on May 30, 1977, in Kochi, Kerala, he began his career as an assistant to music director Ouseppachan. Sundar has composed music for more than 5000 advertisements, programmed music for many major composers, and has worked on over 50 Malayalam films. He has won several awards for his work, including the National Film Award for Best Background Score for the film "1983" and the Kerala State Film Award for Best Music Director for the film "Charlie".

Richie Dorman is a British professional football coach and former player, currently serving as the technical director for SJK Seinäjoki, a football club in the Finnish Veikkausliiga. Born on March 17, 1986, in Liverpool, England, Dorman began his career as a youth player for Liverpool FC before moving to Finland to play for various clubs. After retiring from professional football, he transitioned into coaching and has been with SJK Seinäjoki since 2014. Under his leadership, the club has achieved significant success, including winning the Finnish Cup in 2016.

Grayston Burgess is a renowned English countertenor and conductor, best known for his contributions to the world of classical music. Born on 9 May 1932 in London, he began his musical journey as a chorister at St. Paul's Cathedral. He later studied at the Royal College of Music and became a member of the Deller Consort. Burgess founded the Purcell Consort of Voices in 1963, which he led until 1981. He has performed and recorded extensively, both as a soloist and with his ensemble, and has made significant contributions to the revival of Baroque and Renaissance music.

Arthur Ewert was a German communist political activist and politician who played a significant role in the international communist movement during the early 20th century. Born on February 13, 1890, in Berlin, Germany, Ewert was a member of the Communist Party of Germany and later the Communist International. He was involved in political activities in various countries, including Brazil, where he was arrested and tortured during the dictatorship of Getúlio Vargas. Ewert's health deteriorated due to the torture and he died on August 13, 1959, in East Berlin.

Sir Winston Churchill was a British statesman, army officer, and writer who served as the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom from 1940 to 1945 and again from 1951 to 1955. Born on November 30, 1874, in Woodstock, England, Churchill is best known for his leadership and resilience during World War II, particularly during the London Blitz. He was a prolific writer and won the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1953 for his numerous published works, including a six-volume work The Second World War. Churchill was also known for his inspiring speeches and his refusal to give in when things were going badly. He died on January 24, 1965, in London, England.

The 14th Dalai Lama, Tenzin Gyatso, was born on July 6, 1935, in Taktser, China, at a time when the country was fraught with political unrest. Recognized as the reincarnation of the 13th Dalai Lama at the age of two, he was enthroned in 1940 and assumed full political power in 1950. However, the Chinese invasion of Tibet in 1950 led to the 1959 Tibetan uprising, forcing the Dalai Lama into exile in India. He has since lived in Dharamsala, India, known as "Little Lhasa," where he has established a democratic government in exile. A globally recognized spiritual leader and advocate for peace, the Dalai Lama was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1989 for his nonviolent struggle for Tibet's liberation. He has spent his life teaching Buddhism and advocating for peace and interfaith harmony.

Lodewicus du Plessis is a South African rugby union player who currently plays for the Free State Cheetahs in the Currie Cup and in the Rugby Pro14. Born on 6th May 1993 in Bloemfontein, South Africa, du Plessis primarily plays as a prop. He made his debut for the Free State Cheetahs in 2014 and has since become a key player for the team. Despite his young age, du Plessis has shown great potential and is considered one of the rising stars in South African rugby.

Kaoru Kuroki is a renowned Japanese actress, author, and former adult film star. She was born on April 21, 1968, in Kanagawa Prefecture, Japan. Kuroki gained fame in the late 1980s as a leading actress in the adult film industry, where she was known for her naturalistic performances and refusal to adhere to industry norms. She is credited with popularizing the "no makeup" look in adult films. After retiring from the industry, Kuroki became a successful author and television personality. She is also known for her advocacy work, particularly in relation to sex workers' rights and HIV/AIDS awareness.

Don DeLillo is an acclaimed American novelist, playwright, and essayist, known for his works that explore themes of American life, globalisation, technology, and popular culture. Born on November 20, 1936, in the Bronx, New York, DeLillo published his first novel, "Americana," in 1971. He gained significant recognition with his breakout novel "White Noise" in 1985, which won the National Book Award. His 1997 novel, "Underworld," is often hailed as his masterpiece and was nominated for the National Book Award and the Pulitzer Prize. DeLillo's work is characterized by its satirical, postmodernist style and its profound examination of the impact of consumerism and media on contemporary society.

Ryan Brasier is a professional baseball pitcher who has played for several Major League Baseball (MLB) teams. Born on August 26, 1987, in Wichita Falls, Texas, he was drafted by the Los Angeles Angels in the 2007 MLB Draft. He made his MLB debut with the Angels in 2013. After a brief stint in Japan playing for the Hiroshima Toyo Carp, Brasier returned to the United States and signed with the Boston Red Sox in 2018. He played a key role in the Red Sox's 2018 World Series championship run. As of 2021, he plays for the Los Angeles Angels.

Riccardo Tisci is an esteemed Italian fashion designer known for his work as the creative director of Givenchy from 2005 to 2017. Born on August 8, 1974, in Taranto, Italy, Tisci studied at London's Central Saint Martins College of Art and Design. His unique blend of gothic and streetwear influences, combined with his ability to create compelling couture, made him a standout in the fashion industry. After leaving Givenchy, Tisci took on the role of Chief Creative Officer at Burberry in 2018, where he continues to push boundaries in contemporary fashion.

Joe McGinniss was an American author and journalist, best known for his works in the non-fiction and true crime genres. He was born on December 9, 1942, in New York City and began his career as a newspaper reporter before transitioning into writing books. His first book, "The Selling of the President 1968", which detailed the marketing of Richard Nixon during the 1968 presidential campaign, became an instant bestseller. McGinniss also wrote several true crime books, including "Fatal Vision" and "Blind Faith", both of which were adapted into successful television miniseries. He passed away on March 10, 2014.

Jake Tilson is a renowned British artist, designer, and author known for his innovative approach to graphic design and digital media. Born in 1958, he studied at the Chelsea School of Art and the Royal College of Art in London. Tilson's work often explores themes of urban life, travel, and food, and he has published several books on these subjects. His unique style, which combines photography, drawing, and digital manipulation, has been exhibited in galleries and museums around the world. In addition to his artistic pursuits, Tilson has also taught at various institutions, including the Royal College of Art and the London College of Printing.

Ruth Fischer was a prominent Austrian and German Communist and anti-Stalinist activist. Born in 1895 in Leipzig, Germany, she was one of the founding members of the Austrian Communist Party in 1918. She later served as the leader of the Communist Party of Germany from 1924 to 1925. However, her opposition to Stalin led to her expulsion from the party in 1926. After fleeing to France and then the United States during World War II, she worked as a freelance journalist and writer. Fischer passed away in 1961 in Paris, France.

Eric Winter is an American actor, producer, and former fashion model. He was born on July 17, 1976, in La Mirada, California. Winter is best known for his roles in TV series such as "Days of Our Lives", "The Mentalist", and "The Rookie". He also starred in the film "Harold & Kumar Escape from Guantanamo Bay". Winter began his career as a model before transitioning into acting. He is married to actress Roselyn Sanchez and they have two children together.

Maddy Crippen is a former American competitive swimmer who specialized in middle-distance freestyle and medley events. She was born on March 30, 1980, in Conshohocken, Pennsylvania. Crippen swam for the University of Virginia, where she was a two-time NCAA champion. She also competed in the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia, where she finished sixth in the 400-meter individual medley. After retiring from competitive swimming, Crippen has worked as a swimming analyst for ESPN and Universal Sports. She is the sister of the late Fran Crippen, a world champion open water swimmer.

Mark Murphy was an American jazz singer known for his distinctive vocal style and improvisational skills. Born on March 14, 1932, in Syracuse, New York, Murphy began his musical career in the 1950s and quickly gained recognition for his talent. He released over 40 albums throughout his career, earning him six Grammy nominations. Murphy was particularly noted for his interpretations of the music of Nat King Cole and his ability to vocalese, a jazz singing style where lyrics are set to established jazz instrumental works. He passed away on October 22, 2015, leaving behind a significant legacy in the world of jazz.

Evgeny Shalunov is a professional Russian cyclist, born on January 19, 1992, in Izhevsk, Russia. He began his professional career in 2011 with the Itera-Katusha team. Shalunov has competed in several prestigious cycling events, including the Tour de l'Avenir and the UCI Road World Championships. He is known for his endurance and speed, and has achieved significant results in both road and track cycling. As of 2021, he is a member of the Gazprom-RusVelo team.

Ricky Martin, born Enrique Martin Morales on December 24, 1971, is a Puerto Rican singer, actor, and author who is widely regarded as the "King of Latin Pop". He began his career at the age of 12 as a member of the boy band Menudo. After leaving the group, Martin moved to New York to pursue a solo career, releasing several Spanish-language albums. His breakthrough came in 1999 with the English-language album "Ricky Martin", which included the hit single "Livin' la Vida Loca". The album sold over 15 million copies worldwide, making it one of the best-selling albums of all time. Martin has won numerous awards throughout his career, including two Grammy Awards, and is also known for his humanitarian work through the Ricky Martin Foundation.

Virginia Christine was an American stage, radio, film, television, and voice actress. She was born on March 5, 1920, in Stanton, Iowa, and began her acting career in the 1940s. She is best known for her role as Mrs. Olson in the Folgers Coffee commercials during the 1960s and 1970s. Christine also had notable roles in films such as "Invasion of the Body Snatchers" and "Guess Who's Coming to Dinner". She passed away on July 24, 1996, in Los Angeles, California.

Jean Muir was an American stage and film actress, known for her roles in the 1930s and 1940s. She was born in New York City on February 13, 1911. Muir began her acting career on stage before transitioning to film, where she starred in movies such as "The Constant Nymph" and "A Modern Hero". Her career was cut short in the 1950s when she was blacklisted by the House Un-American Activities Committee for alleged communist sympathies. Despite her attempts to revive her career, she was unable to regain her previous success. Muir later turned to teaching and worked at Stephens College in Missouri. She passed away on July 23, 1996.

Bobby Thomson was a Scottish-born American professional baseball player, best known for his time with the New York Giants. Born on October 25, 1923, in Glasgow, Scotland, Thomson moved to the United States at a young age. He made his Major League Baseball debut in 1946 and played for several teams throughout his career, including the Milwaukee Braves and the Chicago Cubs. However, he is most famous for his "Shot Heard 'Round the World," a game-winning home run in the 1951 National League pennant race that is considered one of the most dramatic moments in baseball history. Thomson retired in 1960 and passed away in 2010.

Chacho Gaytán is a renowned Mexican musician, composer, and producer. He is best known as a member of the popular Latin pop duo, Sentidos Opuestos, which he formed with Alessandra Rosaldo in the early 1990s. The duo achieved significant success in Mexico and other Spanish-speaking countries with hits like "Escribeme en el Cielo" and "Tu y Yo". Apart from his work with Sentidos Opuestos, Gaytán has also worked as a producer for other artists and has composed music for television and film. His contributions to the music industry have earned him several awards and recognitions.

Sayuri Yamauchi is a renowned Japanese voice actress, best known for her work in popular anime series and video games. She was born on January 19, 1957, in Fukuoka, Japan. Throughout her career, she has lent her voice to a variety of characters in popular anime series such as "One Piece," "Naruto," and "Dragon Ball Z." In addition to her work in anime, Yamauchi has also provided voiceovers for video games, including the "Final Fantasy" series. Despite her extensive career, she remains a private individual, keeping her personal life away from the public eye.

Idi Amin Dada, often referred to as "The Butcher of Uganda", was a military dictator who ruled the Republic of Uganda from 1971 to 1979. He remains one of the most brutal leaders in history, known for his erratic behavior, unpredictability, and flair for drama.

Diego Suarez was a renowned landscape architect best known for his work on the Villa Vizcaya in Miami, Florida, and for his profound influence on modern garden design. He operated his own landscape architecture firm until his retirement in 1939. He died in 1974.
